“The Eagles have had a miraculous 52-year odyssey, performing for people all over the globe; keeping the music alive in the face of tragic losses, upheavals and setbacks of many kinds. Credit and thanks go to our longtime management team, our dedicated road crew, and our exceptional backup musicians for providing skilled and steadfast support, throughout these many years. We know how fortunate we are, and we are truly grateful. Our long run has lasted far longer than any of us ever dreamed. But, everything has its time, and the time has come for us to close the circle. The official farewell tour is currently in the planning stages. We want to give all our fans a chance to see us on this final round.  So, scheduling information will be released as dates are set. The difficulties of booking venues for multiple nights may require us to return to certain cities, depending on demand.  But, we hope to see as many of you as we can, before we finish up. Most importantly, we thank you from the bottom of our hearts for embracing this band and its music. At the end of the day, you are the reason we have been able to carry on for over five decades. This is our swan song, but the music goes on and on.”
 
With love and gratitude,
The Eagles
 
Eagles — Don Henley, Joe Walsh and Timothy B. Schmit, with Vince Gill and Deacon Frey - will embark on their final tour, “The Long Goodbye”.

Last night, Country Music Hall of Fame members @VinceGillofficial and Emmylou Harris, along with @AshleyMcBryde and @CarlyPearce, took the stage for "All for the Hall New York," a benefit concert for the Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum’s education programs.

The "All for the Hall" concert is modeled after a Nashville tradition known as a “guitar pull,” a casual affair in which songwriters take turns performing while their fellow artists listen or add accompaniment. The evening unfolded with Gill, Harris, McBryde, and Pearce swapping songs and stories at New York City's @IrvingPlaza.

The evening also showcased the Museum’s flagship education program, "Words & Music," which pairs students with professional songwriters to help them develop language arts skills through songwriting. The video recording of the song "When Hearts Come to Life," written and performed by first-grade "Words & Music" students from Brooklyn's PS32 school, was played for the audience.
All For The Hall, benefitting the @countrymusichof, is returning to Nashville on December 5th at @bridgestonearenaofficial! Tickets are on sale now at the link in bio.

To honor a truly “Beautiful Man” on his 70th birthday, please check out this tribute to the life of Michael Rhodes from Vince’s old friend @rodneyjcrowell and Alison Prestwood. Watch at the link in story.

Last call to share your "Sweet Memories" for a chance to win a signed acoustic guitar and boxset from Vince Gill and Paul Franklin! Some great memories and stories have been shared so far. Enter at the link in bio before the contest ends Friday.

When this publicity shot was taken in 1984, @VinceGillofficial had recently signed to @RCARecords. That year, he landed his first solo single, "Victim of Life's Circumstances," on the country chart. Gill, then in his late twenties, was already a seasoned musician, though, having played with a number of bands, including #BooneCreek (with @RickySkaggs), #PurePrairieLeague, and the Cherry Bombs (with @RodneyJCrowell, #EmoryGordyJr, and Tony Brown (@TBmusicproducer)).

Gill continued to rise through country music’s ranks, and throughout the 1990s, he was one of its dominant artists. He took home Grammys every year in the decade, became a Grand Ole @Opry member in 1991, won Country Music Association awards for Entertainer of the Year in 1993 and 1994, and won the CMA's Male Vocalist of the Year honor in five consecutive years (1991–1995)—a feat no other artist has achieved. Gill is also the only songwriter to win @CMA Song of the Year four times. He began hosting the #CMAAwards in 1992, a tradition he continued through 2003.

Gill was inducted into the #CountryMusicHallofFame in 2007. Through both his career and his advocacy for the preservation of country music history, Gill continues to contribute to the ongoing vitality of the genre.

Last night, four-time Grammy Award winner @KeithUrban and Country Music Hall of Fame member @VinceGillofficial returned to Nashville’s @BridgestoneArenaofficial for Urban’s "All for the Hall" concert, presented by @CityNationalBank, which benefits the Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum.

The concert featured performances by musical directors Urban and Gill, as well as @KelseaBallerini, @ERNEST, Riley Green (@Rileyduckman), @MickeyGuyton, @HARDY, @OldDominionmusic, @TheWarandTreaty, @TrishaYearwood, and Country Music Hall of Fame members @officialBrendaLee, @BrooksandDunn, and #PattyLoveless.

This was Urban’s eighth "All for the Hall Nashville" concert, which raised more than $900,000, the largest amount in the history of the concert series, which has collectively raised more than $5 million in support of the nonprofit Museum and its educational initiatives. The Museum extends a heartfelt thank-you to Keith, Vince, and all those who contributed their time, talent, and support to make the evening possible.
